natural problem: What is the sum of the values of $a$ that satisfy the equation $$(3)5^2-4(5-a)^2 \div 3=63?$$
natural solution: First we multiply all terms in the equation by 3 to avoid fractions and then solve for $a$. \begin{align} 9\cdot5^2-4(5-a)^2&=3\cdot63\quad\Rightarrow\\ -4(5-a)^2&=9\cdot21-9\cdot25\quad\Rightarrow\\ &=9(-4)\quad\Rightarrow\\
(5-a)^2&=9 \end{align} Therefore, \begin{align} 5-a=3\quad\text{ OR }\quad 5-a=-3\quad\Rightarrow\\ 2=a \quad\text{ OR }\quad 8=a. \end{align} The sum of the values of $a$ is $2+8=\boxed{10}$.
